81 respectively reveal the views of Evangelicals who, at either end of the nineteenth century, had a forum for expressing their views from the pinnacle of the church establishment. The major text, the undergraduate diary of Francis Chavasse [1865-8], also written by a future bishop, provides a fascinating insight into the mind of a young Evangelical at Oxford, struggling with his conscience and his calling. Each text is presented with an introduction and notes.Contributors ANDREW ATHERSTONE, MARK SMITH, ANNE STOTT, MARTIN WELLINGS.MARK SMITH teaches at King's College, London; STEPHEN TAYLOR is Reader in Eighteenth Century History, University of Reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEvangelicalismxChurch of EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aEvangelicalismxChurch of EnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aEvangelicalismzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aEvangelicalismzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 7aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Evangelism.2bisacsh  a18th century.  a19th century.  aChristianity.  aChurch of England.  aEvangelicalism in the Church of England c.1790-c.1890^Evangelicalism.  areligious movement.1 aAtherstone, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStott, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Stephen C, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTaylor, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWellings, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eB